  "response_text": "First, let's solve the system of equations:\n\n1) \\(3x + 2y = 12\\)\n2) \\(x - y = 1\\)\n\nWe can use substitution or elimination to solve for \\(x\\) and \\(y\\). Let's use substitution.\n\nFrom equation 2), we have:\n\\[x = y + 1\\]\n\nNow substitute \\(x = y + 1\\) into equation 1):\n\\[3(y + 1) + 2y = 12\\]\n\nSimplify and solve for \\(y\\):\n\\[3y + 3 + 2y = 12\\]\n\\[5y + 3 = 12\\]\n\\[5y = 9\\]\n\\[y = \\frac{9}{5}\\]\n\nNow that we have \\(y\\), we can find \\(x\\) using \\(x = y + 1\\):\n\\[x = \\frac{9}{5} + 1\\]\n\\[x = \\frac{9}{5} + \\frac{5}{5}\\]\n\\[x = \\frac{14}{5}\\]\n\nSo, the solution is:\n\\[x = \\frac{14}{5}, \\quad y = \\frac{9}{5}\\]\n\nThe final answer is:\n\\[x = \\frac{14}{5}, \\quad y = \\frac{9}{5}\\]",
